  "text": "The Apache Kafka authorization audit logging system consists of multiple components that work together to log authorization decisions (ALLOWED and DENIED events):\n\n1. **Audit Logging Layer (metadata module)**:\n   - StandardAuthorizerData.java is the core implementation that performs the actual audit logging. It contains the `authorize(AuthorizableRequestContext, Action)` method which calls `logAuditMessage()` at line 250. This method logs authorization decisions with different log levels: DEBUG for ALLOWED operations when logIfAllowed is true (line 292), and INFO for DENIED operations when logIfDenied is true (line 305). The audit logger \"kafka.authorizer.logger\" is created at line 116.\n   - StandardAuthorizer.java implements the Authorizer interface and delegates authorization to StandardAuthorizerData. It also records metrics for ALLOWED and DENIED events in the AuthorizerMetrics inner class (lines 253-257).\n\n2. **Authorization Decision Classes (clients module)**:\n   - Action.java (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/server/authorizer/) defines the action being authorized with flags logIfAllowed() and logIfDenied() that control whether the authorization decision should be logged to the audit trail.\n   - AuthorizationResult.java defines the ALLOWED and DENIED enum values that represent authorization outcomes.\n   - Authorizer.java is the pluggable interface that brokers use for authorization, which implementations like StandardAuthorizer must implement.\n\n3. **Authorization Request Handling (core module)**:\n   - AuthHelper.scala provides helper methods (authorize, filterByAuthorized, partitionSeqByAuthorized) that call the authorizer's authorize() method and pass the logIfAllowed and logIfDenied flags to control audit logging behavior.\n   - KafkaApis.scala handles broker-side request processing and calls AuthHelper.authorize() for various operations like Produce, Metadata, OffsetCommit, and others, specifying whether to log allowed/denied operations.\n   - ControllerApis.scala handles controller-side request processing and similarly calls authHelper.authorize() for operations like CreateTopics, DeleteTopics, and AlterConfigs.\n   - AclApis.scala handles ACL management requests (CreateAcls, DeleteAcls, DescribeAcls) and authorizes these requests before processing them.\n\nThe audit logging flow is: Request Handler (KafkaApis/ControllerApis) -> AuthHelper.authorize() -> StandardAuthorizer.authorize() -> StandardAuthorizerData.authorize() -> logAuditMessage() which logs to the \"kafka.authorizer.logger\" with messages containing authorization status (Allowed/Denied) along with principal, operation, resource, and host information."
